# Caddy reverse proxy for serving the studio over HTTPS on the LAN so a
# phone (or any second device) can hit /capture and have the browser
# accept getUserMedia. Without HTTPS, mobile browsers refuse the camera
# request — only `localhost` is exempt, and you can't loopback from a
# phone.
#
# Wired up with mkcert: `make up-https` runs scripts/mkcert-bootstrap.sh,
# which installs mkcert on the host, trusts a local root CA, generates
# a cert pair into ./caddy/certs/, and copies the root CA next to it so
# this Caddyfile can serve it back over plain HTTP for the phone to
# download (the phone has to trust the CA *before* it'll accept the
# studio's HTTPS cert — chicken-and-egg).
#
# Both blocks bind to ports rather than hostnames so the LAN IP and the
# friendly `studio.local` name both work without any DNS setup; the
# cert SANs cover both. If you do set up DNS / mDNS, that just works
# too.

# Plain HTTP block — its only jobs are:
#   1. serve /mkcert-rootCA.pem so the phone can download the root CA
#      before it trusts anything HTTPS.
#   2. redirect every other request to HTTPS.
:80 {
	@rootca path /mkcert-rootCA.pem
	handle @rootca {
		root * /certs
		rewrite * /rootCA.pem
		file_server
	}
	handle {
		redir https://{host}{uri} permanent
	}
}

# HTTPS block — proxies to the studio. /api/* hits FastAPI (HTTP +
# WebSocket; Caddy upgrades the WS automatically when the client sends
# the Upgrade header). Everything else hits the Next.js web container.
# Same hostname for both so the capture WebSocket stays same-origin.
:443 {
	tls /certs/cert.pem /certs/key.pem
	reverse_proxy /api/* api:8000
	reverse_proxy * web:3000
}
